\begin_layout Subsection
The Accounting Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2 adjustments are made to the accounting B/S to transform it:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Subtract the operational liabilities from the working capital to get the
 net working capital.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Subtract the excess financial assets from the financial liabilities.
 The logic is to assume that all the excess financial assets can pay the
 liabilities.
 It is a financial (not an economic) decision.
 Even though usually all the cash & equivalents is used, a more advanced
 approach is to first figure out how much of it is needed (e.g cash registry),
 then split the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cash
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 asset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an example with a firm that has assets, liabilities and equity
 equal to 100, 60 and 40 respectively.
 What owning 90% of the firm means? Counterintuitively, having full control
 of the firm, all assets are owned.
 The equity of 40 is composed of 30 owned + 10 for non-controlling interest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Example - TSLA analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each line in the B/S is first categorized, in order to calculate the total
 values for each of the assets/liabilities subcategories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Patents are usually not included in the the B/S as intangible assets, unless
 they were purchased.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Non-controlling interest can be considered as a financial liability, as
 failure to meet the obligations might end up with a bankruptcy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the economic balance sheet is calculated.
\end_layout

